ollowing people, as of 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"2R\"/><ref name=\"18R\">{{cite web|date=17 April 2018 | url=https://www.umeme.co.ug/board-of-directors/ |title=Umeme Limited: Board of Directors |access-date=17 April 2018 | publisher=Umeme Limited |author=Umeme |location=Kampala}}</ref><ref name=\"19R\">{{cite web |url=http://observer.ug/special-editions/57702-umeme-shareholders-reject-bigirimana-over-tainted-corrupt-image.html | title=Umeme shareholders reject Bigirimana over 'tainted, corrupt image' |access-date=18 May 2018 |date=17 May 2018 |author=URN | newspaper=[[The Observer (Uganda)]] Quoting [[Uganda Radio Network]] (URN) |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 0.5em auto\"\n|+ Board of Directors of Umeme Limited\n! Rank !! Director !! Position !! Nationality !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || [[Patrick Bitature]] || [[Chairman]] || [[Uganda]]n || \n|-\n| 2 || [[Selestino Babungi]] || [[Managing Director]] || Ugandan || \n|-\n| 3 || [[Gerald Ssendaula]] || Non-Executive Director || Ugandan || \n|-\n| 4 || Pieter Adriaan Falling || Non-Executive Director || [[South Africa]]n || \n|-\n| 5 || [[Florence Mawejje|Florence Namatta Mawejje]] || Non-Executive Director || Ugandan || \n|-\n| 6 || [[Florence Mawejje|Florence Namatta Mawejje]] || Non-Executive Director || Ugandan || \n|-\n| 7 || Andrew Buglass ||Non-Executive Director \u00a0 ||[[Britain|British]] || \n|-\n| 8 || Anthony Marsh ||Non-Executive Director \u00a0 || British ||\n|-\n| 9 || Stephen Emasu || Non-Executive Director || Ugandan ||<ref name=\"20R\">{{cite web|title=Umeme deputy MD Sam Zimbe to retire | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Bigirimana-ex-EU-envoy-named-Umeme-board/688334-4420694-5jtqb3/index.html |date=17 April 2018 |access-date=17 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | location=Kampala}}</ref> \n|-\n| 10 || Riccardo Ridolfi ||Non-Executive Director ||[[Italy|Italian]] ||<ref name=\"20R\"/> \n|-\n| 11 ||[[Florence Nsubuga|Florence Nakimbugwe Nsubuga]] || [[Executive Director]] ||Ugandan || \n|-\n|'''Total'''  ||<center>'''11'''</center> ||  ||  ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Management structure==\nUmeme is structured into twelve management departments, each headed by a senior manager. The senior managers form the Executive Committee, whose members were the following as of 1 June 2018:<ref name=\"21R\">{{cite web|access-date=1 June 2018 | url=https://www.umeme.co.ug/senior-management-team/ |title=Umeme Limited Senior Management Team |date=1 June 2018 |author=Umeme | location=Kampala |publisher=Umeme Limited}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n|+ Umeme Senior Management Structure\n|-\n! style=\"width:2em;\" |Department!!Name of Manager!!Title of Officer\n|-\n| [[Managing Director|Office of the Managing Director]] || [[Selestino Babungi]] || [[Managing Director]]\n|-\n| [[Operations Management]] || [[Florence Nsubuga]] || [[Chief Operations Officer]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Umeme to realign operations with two new appointments |  accessdate=6 May 2014 |  url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Commodities/-/688610/1325502/-/dgl2u5/-/ | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | last=Ladu | date=13 February 2012 | location=Kampala |first=Ismail Musa}}</ref>\n|-\n| Technical Office || Simbiso Chimbima ||[[Chief Technical Officer]]\n|-\n| [[Corporate development|Corporate Development]] || Blessing Nshaho || Chief Corporate and Regulatory Officer\n|-\n| [[General Manager]] || [[Almero Grey]] ||Acting General Manager Capital and Contracts Division\n|-  \n| Finance || Ross Masterman ||[[Chief Financial Officer]]\n|-\n| [[Information Systems]] ||Roger Bentley ||Chief Information Officer\n|-\n| [[Internal Audit]] || [[Ruth Doreen Mutebe]] || [[Internal Audit|Head of Internal Audit]] \n|-\n| Customer Service || [[Agnes Nalwanga]] || [[Customer service|Head of Customer Service]]\n|-\n| [[Supply chain|Supply Chain]] ||Patrice Namisano||\nHead of Supply Chain\n|-\n|}\n\nUnder the Executive Committee, Umeme has 25 other managers who assist the executives to implement company policy and run the company on a daily basis. In March 2015, [[Selestino Babungi]] was appointed managing director, replacing Charles Chapman who served in that role from February 2009 until March 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title=Electricity utility boss resigns | url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1212866/electricity-utility-boss-resigns | accessdate=17 February 2016|date=20 May 2009 | newspaper=[[New Vision]] | location=Kampala | last=Vision Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Unreliability of service==\n[[File:UMEME-Outages-Kampala-Kibuli.png|thumb|300px|A graph showing frequent power outages in the Kibuli area of Kampala during the month of April 2016.]]\n\nWithin Uganda, Umeme is known for chronic unreliability and has been accused of corruption.<ref>{{cite web | location=Kampala | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Kadaga-orders-Umeme-bribery-claims-probe/-/688334/2107424/-/15qbmeyz/-/index.html | date=11 December 2013 | title=Kadaga orders Umeme bribery claims probe | accessdate=17 February 2016 | first=and Isaac Imaka | last=Nelson Wesonga | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]}}</ref> Customers frequently face extended service outages,<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=17 February 2016 | url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/Umeme-cuts-energy-losses-large-consumers-still-decry-poor-supply/-/2560/2921924/-/t20snq/-/index.html | title=Power cuts: No respite for Umeme's large users | newspaper=[[The East African]] | first=Bernard | last=Busuulwa | location=Nairobi | date=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=World Bank | url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/IC.ELC.OUTG | title=Power outages in firms in a typical month (number) | publisher=[[World Bank]] | accessdate=17 February 2016 | date=2014 | location=Washington, D. C.}}</ref> which are occasionally followed by protests, riots, and assaults on Umeme employees.\n\n===Protests and rioting===\n\nIn 2010, protests erupted after a two-week power blackout in the town of [[Bugembe]]. Attempts to disperse the protesters led to violent clashes between police and irate residents. Nine were arrested, with eight being charged with inciting violence, staging an unlawful and violent assembly, and insulting the police.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=17 February 2016 | title=8 Ugandans remanded over Jinja Umeme riot | location=Kampala | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/-/688334/1056406/-/cl5yjhz/-/index.html | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | date=19 November 2010 | last=Gulumaire | first=Andrew}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, a two-month power outage led to protests in [[Jinja, Uganda|Jinja]]. Residents and business owners built barricades, set tires ablaze, and blocked traffic. Police responded with [[tear gas]] and live ammunition.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=17 February 2016 | last=Biryabarema | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uganda-electricity-idUSL5E7N14FV20111202 | title= Uganda power cuts provoke riots, threaten economy | first=Elias | date=2 December 2016 | publisher=[[Reuters.com]]}}</ref> Days later, over 100 people were dispersed by riot police using tear gas and rubber bullets after marching on Umeme's offices in protest of recurring outages in [[Masaka]] town.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=17 February 2016 | date=4 December 2011 | url=http://www.observer.ug/news-headlines/16171-police-take-over-umeme-officesPolice | first= Sadab | last=Kitatta Kaaya | title=Police take over Umeme offices | newspaper=[[The Observer (Uganda)]] | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, after a month-long outage along the [[Kampala\u2013Gayaza Road]], stone-throwing protesters caused property damage and injuries.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chimpreports.com/3745-umeme-riots-rock-kampala-wakiso | title=Umeme Riots Rock Kampala, Wakiso  | accessdate=17 February 2016 | date=17 January 2012 | last=Administrator | publisher=Chipreports.com | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, a Umeme manager in Mubende was beaten severely by an infuriated mob during power-related protests at the Kasambya trading centre. The ensuing battle between rioters and security forces resulted in 15 arrests and one other injury, including a trader who was shot twice.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1340074/umeme-boss-beaten-mob-mubende | title=Umeme boss beaten by mob in Mubende | accessdate=13 February 2016 | date=26 April 2014 | newspaper=[[New Vision]] | first=Luke | last=Kagiri | location=Kampala}}</ref> Later that year, Kampala print and publishing shop owners went on strike, blocked Nasser road, and burnt paper and plastic to protest six-day power cuts along the road. Security forces used tear gas to disperse the protesters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Nasser-Road-traders-riot-after-6-days-power-outage/-/688334/2456822/-/mq91f9/-/index.html | title=Nasser Road traders riot after 6 days power outage | accessdate=17 February 2016 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | first=Stephen | last=Kafeero | date=18 September 2014 | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, hundreds of people demonstrated in front of Umeme's office in Gulu Town in north Uganda. Many people involved in business were complaining that the frequent power outages raise their costs and prevent them from properly managing their ventures. The crowd was joined by MPs supportive of the protesters. Although the demonstration was peaceful, security forces fired teargas to stop it. One person was shot in the buttock.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.softpower.ug/mps-otto-olanya-join-gulu-protest-against-frequent-power-cuts-by-umeme/|title=MPs Otto, Olanya Join Gulu Protest Against Frequent Power Cuts by Umeme|date=2018-12-03|website=Online news from Uganda and the East African region - SoftPower News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===Recommendations by parliament===\n\nIn 2013, a probe committee of Uganda's Parliament recommended cancellation of Umeme's contract due to its chronic failure to provide reliable services, which would trigger a contract severance payment of at least US$148 million.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/Uganda-faces-high-bill-to-end-Umeme-deal/-/2558/2067012/-/m5t79c/-/index.html | title=Uganda faces high bill to end Umeme deal | newspaper=[[The East African]] | accessdate=17 February 2016 | location=Nairobi | first=Halima | last=Abdallah}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, Uganda's Parliament recommended that Umeme's \"contract should be terminated\u201d due to the gross manipulations encountered in the procurement of the Umeme concession, and the scandalous provisions of the power distribution agreements signed between the government of Uganda and Umeme.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.parliament.go.ug/new/index.php/about-parliament/parliamentary-news/367-terminate-umeme-and-eskom-contracts-parliament | title=Terminate Umeme and Eskom Contracts | publisher=parliament.go.ug | location=Uganda | date=27 March 2014 | accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> Ultimately, this course of action was decided against because it would have been too expensive and politically complicated.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.observer.ug/business/79-businesstopstories/31128--why-umeme-contract-will-not-be-terminated | title=Why Umeme contract will not be terminated  | publisher=Observer | location=Uganda | date=8 April 2014 | accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Power losses==\nIn June 2016, Umeme estimated its total power losses across its network at 19.1 percent.<ref name=\"Losses\">{{cite web | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201609210057.html | title=Uganda: Power Theft Loss Rises to Shs100 Billion | first=Jonathan | last=Adengo | work=[[Daily Monitor|The Monitor]] | location=[[Kampala]] | via=AllAfrica | date=21 September 2016 | access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> In September 2016, Umeme estimated that it lost UGX:106 billion annually from nonpayment of bills, vandalism, and illegal connections.<ref name=\"Losses\"/> Fifty-one percent of its losses come from the [[Bugisu sub-region]] in the [[Eastern Region, Uganda|Eastern Region]].<ref name=\"Losses\"/>\n\nIn June 2015, Umeme estimated its power losses at 19.2 percent. Of that, 13 percent was attributable to technical losses (resulting from poor network configuration) and 6.2 percent was from commercial losses (such as power theft and under-billing). In 2017, Umeme's power losses were reduced to 17.2 percent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Umeme lauds government policy on power thieves | url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1486815/umeme-lauds-government-policy-power-thieves |newspaper=[[New Vision]] | date=2 October 2018 |access-date=20 December 2018 |author=Vision Reporter |location=Kampala}}</ref> Umeme planned to reduce total power loss to 15 percent by 2018.<ref>{{cite web |access-date=4 June 2016 |date=12 December 2015 |newspaper=[[The EastAfrican]]  |url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/East-Africa-electricity-firms-in-bid-to-reduce-power-losses-/-/2560/2993832/-/b69sviz/-/index.html |title=East Africa electricity firms in bid to reduce power losses |last=Anyanzwa | first=James |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn May 2010, Umeme's communications director Charlotte Kemigyisha wrote a commentary in the ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' newspaper urging public support for President [[Yoweri Museveni]]'s proposal to make electricity theft a [[capital offense]].<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=13 February 2016 | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/-/689364/913414/-/view/printVersion/-/xm00v6z/-/index.html | title=Make electricity vandalism a capital offence | first=Charlotte | last=Kemigyisha | date=May 2010 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Umeme announced plans to invest US$32 million during 2011 in new substations, improvements in grid connectivity, and the introduction of pre-payment systems.<ref>{{cite web | title=Umeme Uganda to Invest $32 Million in Power Substations in 2011 | accessdate=6 May 2014 | first=Fred | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-30/umeme-uganda-to-invest-32-million-in-power-substations-systems-in-2011.html | date=30 November 2010 | last=Ojambo | publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Umeme announced that it had secured loans totaling US$190 million from the [[International Finance Corporation]], [[Standard Chartered Bank]], and [[Stanbic Bank]] to fund grid expansion and reduce energy losses.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=17 February 2016 | date=13 November 2013 | url=http://in.reuters.com/article/uganda-umeme-loan-idINL5N0IY0YT20131113 | title=Ugandan power firm Umeme gets $190 million for grid expansion | publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] | last=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nUmeme is spending US$440 million between 2013 and 2018 to overhaul equipment, buy technology, and add distribution points.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-10/umeme-will-invest-up-to-100m-upgrading-uganda-network-this-year | title=Umeme Will Invest Up to $100m Upgrading Uganda Network This Year | accessdate=17 February 2016 | date=9 April 2015 | first=Fred | last=Ojambo | publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' newspaper reported that Umeme had signed a contract with the [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] to distribute the power generated from the [[Isimba Hydroelectric Power Station]], due online in 2018, and the [[Karuma Hydroelectric Power Station]], due online in 2020.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=23 March 2016 | date=23 March 2016 | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Markets/Umeme-to-distribute-Karuma--Isimba-power/-/688606/3129418/-/3fi5ia/-/index.html | title=Umeme to distribute Karuma, Isimba power | location=Kampala |\nnewspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | first=Mark Keith | last=Muhumuza}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, a senior Umeme executive said that the company planned to spend US$2 billion over the next five years to expand the grid and increase access rates from an estimated 20 percent in 2016 (about 900,000 subscribers) to 40 percent in 2020 (about 3 million subscribers).<ref>{{cite web | date=22 September 2016 | url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/Uganda-to-spend-USD2-billion-on-power-connections-and-grid/2560-3391022-9pe5w7z/index.html | accessdate=22 September 2016 | newspaper=[[The EastAfrican]] Quoting [[Reuters]] | first=George | last=Obulutsa | title=Uganda to spend $2 billion on power connections, grid}}</ref> In December 2017, Umeme announced plans to invest US$155 million in 2018, to improve the distribution network, build new substations and refurbish old networks across Uganda.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=27 December 2017 | url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201712270144.html |title=Uganda: Umeme to Invest US$155 Million in 2018 | date=27 December 2017 | location=Kampala | newspaper=[[The Independent (Uganda)|The Independent]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] |author=The Independent}}</ref> In May 2018, in an interview with [[Reuters]], Celestino Babungi, the [[CEO]] of Umeme, announced that the company planned to raise US$1.2 billion to revamp and expand the national distribution grid over the next seven years. A consultant was hired to advise and guide on how to raise the funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFL5N1SN1L6 |title=Uganda power distributor Umeme to spend $1.2 bln to expand grid |access-date=31 July 2018 |date=16 May 2018 | first=Elias |last=Biryabarema |publisher=[[Reuters|Reuters Africa]] |location=Johannesburg}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the [[Daily Monitor]] newspaper reported that Umeme planned to borrow US$70 million from the [[International Finance Corporation]] to add to the US$255 million raised internally, in order to invest in network upgrades and expansion while reducing network losses along with increased collection targets during the 2019\u20132024 time frame.<ref name=\"UpgradeR\">{{cite news| url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Finance/Umeme-seeks-Shs262b-loan-to-fund-final-leg-of-concession--/688608-5156488-el98s3z/index.html |title=Umeme Seeks Shs262 Billion Loan To Fund Final Leg Of Concession |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |date=14 June 2019 |access-date=17 June 2019 |author=Christine Kasemiire |location=kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Umeme received a syndicated loan of US$70 million from four financial institutions as laid down in the table below. A portion of the loan will be utilized to set up distribution systems to effectively distribute power from [[Isimba Power Station|Isimba]] and [[Karuma Power Station| Karuma]]. Part of the loan will also support extension of power to industrial parks, upgrading Umeme's network, building the backbone on which more electricity connections will be supplied, accelerate prepayment metering and reduce energy losses. Two hundred and thirty thousand customers out of the 1.4 million customers that Umeme services, as of December 2019, are in the process of being converted from post-service billing to pre-paid metering. At that time, total energy losses stood at 16.7 percent, of which 11.7 percent were technical and 5 percent were commercial.<ref name=\"SyndLR\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Finance/Umeme-secures-Shs258-billion-syndicated-loan-for-investment/688608-5384176-3cru1l/index.html |title=Umeme secures Shs258 billion syndicated loan for investment |date=13 December 2019 |access-date=13 December 2019 |author=Christine Kasemiire | place=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 0.5em auto\"\n|+ Umeme Syndicated Loan, December 2019: Sources<ref name=\"SyndLR\"/>\n! Rank !! Lender !! Amount in US Dollars !! Percentage !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || [[International Finance Corporation]] || 28.00 million || 40.00 || Loan\n|-\n| 2 || [[Stanbic Bank Uganda Limited]] || 16.0 million || 22.85 || Loan\n|-\n| 3 || [[Standard Chartered Uganda]] || 16.0 million || 22.85 || Loan\n|-\n| 4 ||[[Netherlands Development Finance Company]] ||10.0 million||14.30 ||Loan\n|-\n| || '''Total''' || '''70.0 million''' || '''100.00''' ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Customer base==\nAs of January 2016, Umeme's customer base was about 790,000, with approximately 16,000 customers being added every month. The company expected its customer base to exceed 1 million by the end of 2016.<ref>{{cite web |newspaper=[[The EastAfrican]] |  url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/Umeme-customer-base-to-hit-1-million-in-2016-/-/2560/3026892/-/15qveya/-/index.html | title=Umeme customer base to hit 1 million in 2016 |last=Wakabi  |accessdate=12 January 2016 | date=9 January 2016 | first=Michael |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\nAs at 30 June 2017, Umeme exceeded 1,000,000 paying customers, with the numbers growing at a rate of 13 percent annually.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://eagle.co.ug/2017/12/08/umeme-customers-now-scale-one-million-mark.html | title=Umeme customers now scale the one million mark | access-date=10 January 2018 |\ndate=8 December 2017 | author=The Eagle Reporter |\npublisher=Eagle.co.ug (The Eagle)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|\nurl=https://ugandaradionetwork.com/story/umeme-customers-hit-the-one-million-mark |title=Umeme Customers Hit One Million Mark | access-date=16 March 2018 |date=11 May 2017 |location=Kampala\n|publisher=[[Uganda Radio Network]] |first=David |last=Rupiny}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Daily Monitor]]'', as of April 2018, Umeme had  1,125,291 customers.<ref name=\"Many\">{{cite web|date=8 April 2018 |url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Umeme-recover-Shs104-billion-domestic-customers/688334-4377642-g7ur03/index.html | title=Umeme to recover Shs104 billion from domestic customers | access-date=17 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |first=Nelson |last=Wesonga |location=Kampala}}</ref> Seventy percent of those customers were on the pre-paid metering system, known as \"Yaka\".<ref name=\"Num\">{{cite web| url=https://www.independent.co.ug/umeme-tremendously-contributed-towards-power-distribution/ |title=Umeme investment in power distribution infrastructure paying off |access-date=17 April 2018 |date=22 November 2017 |newspaper=[[The Independent (Uganda)]] |author=The Uganda Independent |location=Kampala}}</ref> By June 2019, Umeme's customer base exceeded 1.4 million connections.<ref name=\"ExtendR\"/>\n\nBy July 2018, pre-paid metering covered an estimated 80 percent of all Umeme's customers.<ref name=\"50R\">{{cite web|date=12 July 2018 | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Uganda-electricity-sector-critical-crossroads/688322-4659606-3dyoc3z/index.html | last=Wakabi |first=Michael |title=Uganda\u2019s electricity sector at a critical crossroads |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |\nlocation=Kampala |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> At that time, the customer mix was as illustrated in the table below:<ref name=\"50R\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 0.5em auto\"\n|+ Umeme Customer Profile As At July 2018\n! Rank !!Customer Type!!% Consumption!!Cost per kWh (USD)\n|-\n| 1 || Industrial Customers||<center> 65 || 0.10\n|-\n| 2 || Commercial Customers ||<center> 12 ||0.18\n|-\n| 3 || Domestic Customers ||<center>23 || 0.20\n|-\n| ||'''Total'''||<center>'''100.00'''||\n|-\n|}\n\nAs of December 2018, Umeme serviced more than 1.3 million customers, representing an estimated 25 percent of Uganda's population.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 March 2019 |access-date=26 March 2019 |url=https://www.busiweek.com/umeme-sets-aside-us70-million-for-network-upgrade-despite-contract-uncertainty/ |title=Umeme Sets Aside US$70 Million For Network Upgrade Despite Contract Uncertainty |newspaper=[[East Africa Business Week]] |\nfirst=Paul |last=Tentena |location=Kampala}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1496929/umeme-registers-13m-connections |title=Umeme Registers 1.3 Million New Connections |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |date=25 March 2019 | access-date=26 March 2019 |author=David Lumu |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, Umeme serviced in excess of 1.5 million customers, of whom 1.47 million (98 percent) were on the prepaid metering service called \"Yaka\".<ref>{{cite web|date=6 April 2020 |url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Commodities/-power-service-charges-utility-firms-Umeme-ERA-NWSC/688610-5515876-h8rxk8/index.html |title=We have no power to cut or raise service charges, utility firms say |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |\nauthor=Ashita Chopra |access-date=7 April 2020 | place=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Negotiation of new contract==\nIn December 2018, President [[Yoweri Museveni]] instructed [[Irene Muloni]], Uganda's Energy Minister to begin negotiations with Umeme regarding the renewal of the energy concession, when the current contract expires in 2025. The ministry of energy, the ministry of finance and the office of the attorney general will represent Uganda during these negotiations.<ref name=\"52R\">{{cite news|url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Finance/Negotiate-extension-of-Umeme-concession-Museveni-directs/688608-4901056-43jk1pz/index.html |title=Negotiate extension of Umeme concession, Museveni directs |date=19 December 2018 |access-date=19 December 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |first=Nelson |last=Wesonga |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 June 2019, during the reading of the national budget for the financial year 2019/2020, [[Ministry of Finance, Planning and Economic Development (Uganda)|Uganda's Finance Minister]], [[Matia Kasaija]] indicated that that the government will extend Umeme's power distribution concession beyond 2025. Fresh negotiations will be held to finalize the details.<ref name=\"ExtendR\">{{cite news|title=Government to extend Umeme concession |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |date=14 June 2019 |\nurl=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Government-Museveni-extend-Umeme-concession-Kasaija/688334-5157582-nkntsoz/index.html |access-date=14 June 2019 |author=Monitor Reporter | location=Kampala}}</ref> Those negotiations started in February 2020.<ref name=\"NegoR\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Technology/Govt-starts-discussing-renewal-Umeme-20-year-concession/688612-5460784-3kuor1/index.html |title=Government starts discussing renewal of Umeme 20-year concession |date=19 February 2020 |access-date=20 February 2020 |author=Christine Kasemiire |place=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Uganda|Energy}}\n* [[List of power stations in Uganda]]\n* [[West Nile Rural Electrification Company]]\n* [[Energy in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Umeme-issues-Shs340b-investment-plan-for-2016/-/688322/3006744/-/inw9vjz/-/index.html \"Umeme issues Shs340b investment plan\"]\n* [https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/-/2560/2318000/-/62ttei/-/index.html \"Umeme pegs $440m plan on power output rise\"]\n* [http://www.era.or.ug/ Uganda Electricity Regulatory Authority]\n\n{{Kampala District}}\n{{coord|00|19|00|N|32|34|46|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Energy companies of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Kampala District]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Nairobi Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Uganda Securities Exchange]]\n[[Category:Energy in Uganda]]\n", "name_user": "Fsmatovu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Britain\u2192United Kingdom", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umeme"}
{"title_page": "Brett Crozier", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{redirect|Captain Crozier|the Irish polar explorer|Francis Crozier}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|United States Navy officer}}\n\n{{infobox military person\n|name=Brett E. Crozier\n|image=Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg\n|birth_name=Brett Elliott Crozier<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/102nd-congress/852 |title=PN852 \u2014 Navy |date=March 3, 1992 |website=[[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|02|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], [[California]], U.S.\n|allegiance=[[United States of America]]\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|rank=[[File:US Navy O6 infobox.svg|23px]] [[Captain_(United_States_O-6)#U.S._Navy|Captain]] (U.S. rank O-6)<!---specified O-6 to avoid confusion with the more widely known but much lower O-3 rank in the army that bears the same name, for the understanding of ordinary readers not having specialist knowledge--->\n|serviceyears=1992\u2013present\n|commands=[[VFA-94]]<br/>{{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}<br/>{{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71}}\n|battles=[[Iraq War]]\n|awards=[[File:Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|23px]] [[Legion of Merit]] (2) <small>([[#Honors, awards, and decorations|more]])</small>\n}}\n'''Brett Elliott Crozier''' (born February 24, 1970) is a [[Captain_(United_States_O-6)#U.S._Navy|Captain]] in the [[United States Navy]]. He served as [[commanding officer]] of the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']] until being relieved on April 2, 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Courtney|last=Kube|first2=Mosheh|last2=Gains|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier|work=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCrozier grew up in [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], California, graduating from [[Santa Rosa High School (Santa Rosa, California)|Santa Rosa High School]] in 1988 and then entering the [[U.S. Naval Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10310811-181/chris-smith-santa-rosa-high |archive-url=https://archive.is/uI1PU |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Santa Rosa High grad and \u2018Top Gun\u2019 fan now commands the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt |date=November 14, 2019 |last1=Smith |first1=Chris |publisher=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref> He graduated from the Academy in 1992. He received his Master\u2019s Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies from the [[Naval War College]] in 2007, and completed [[Nuclear Power School]] in 2014.<ref name=\"NavyBio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/Pages/COMMANDINGOFFICER.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/ZJbJV |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Captain Brett E. Crozier |publisher=US Navy}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nCrozier was designated a [[naval aviator]] in 1994, and was assigned as a [[SH-60B Seahawk]] pilot to HSL-37 at Barbers Point, Hawaii. He deployed on board {{USS|Crommelin|FFG-37|6}} and {{USS|Fletcher|DD-992|6}} for operations in the Pacific Ocean and [[Operation Southern Watch]] in the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref name = blueridge>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/lcc19/Pages/Bio1-9June2017-16June2018.aspx|title=Captain Brett E. Crozier|website=www.public.navy.mil|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Crozier served in Navy Personnel Command as an aviation detailer and retention program manager. He then shifted to flying the [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18 Hornet]]. In 2002, he reported to [[VFA-97|Strike Fighter Squadron 97 (VFA-97)]], the \"Warhawks\"; the following year, the squadron deployed with {{USS|Nimitz}} in support of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] (OIF).<ref name = blueridge/>\n\nIn 2004, Crozier reported to [[VFA-94|Strike Fighter Squadron 94 (VFA-94)]], another F/A-18 Hornet unit known as the Mighty Shrikes, as a department head, and was again deployed with ''Nimitz'' in 2005. In 2006, Crozier was assigned to [[VFA-125]], the \"Rough Raiders,\" and served as an instructor and Fleet Replacement Squadron Operations Officer. The following year, he reported in 2007 to the Naval War College, where he earned a Master's Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies. \n\nCrozier later served as the [[executive officer]], then commanding officer of VFA-94, based at Naval Station Lemoore in California. As squadron CO, he made multiple deployments for U.S. [[United States Third Fleet|Third]], [[United States Fifth Fleet|Fifth]], and [[United States Seventh Fleet|Seventh Fleet]] operations, numerous exercises and Operations Southern Watch and OIF.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> He led his squadron on expeditionary deployments with [[Marine Aircraft Group 12]] based out of [[Marine Corps Air Station Iwakuni]], Japan, to support Pacific operations and the [[Global War on Terror]]. His squadron CO tour ended in August 2010. \n\nCrozier then reported to [[Naval Striking and Support Forces NATO]] in [[Naples]], Italy, and served as the lead air planner for Joint Task Force Odyssey Dawn and Combined Joint Task Force Deputy Director of Targeting for NATO's Operation Unified Protector.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> \n\nFrom April 2014 until July 2016, Crozier completed the naval nuclear power training program and served as the executive officer of {{USS|Ronald Reagan}}. During this tour,  ''Reagan'' took part in [[Rim of the Pacific|RIMPAC 2014]], two maintenance availabilities, a forward deployment to [[Yokosuka, Japan]], to relieve {{USS|George Washington|CVN-73|6}} as the U.S. Navy's only forward-deployed aircraft carrier, and several Forward Deployed Naval Force deployments in the [[United States Indo-Pacific Command]] area of responsibility.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> From June 2017 to November 2018, he commanded the amphibious command ship {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19|6}} while the ship completed an extensive dry-dock refit and then returned to operations at sea.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> He was assigned command of the [[Nuclear propulsion|nuclear]] [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in November 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/us/politics/coronavirus-aircraft-carrier-roosevelt-crozier.html|title=He Led a Top Navy Ship. Now He Sits in Quarantine, Fired and Infected.|last1=Schmitt|first1=Eric|last2=Ismay|first2=John|date=April 5, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 outbreak onboard ''Theodore Roosevelt''===\n[[File:CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg|thumb|right|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019, one month before Crozier took command of the vessel]]\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\nCrozier was captain of ''Theodore Roosevelt'', then deployed in the Pacific, on March 24, 2020 when reports indicated that three members of the crew had tested positive for [[COVID-19]]. The next day the number of affected sailors was increased to eight, and within a few days it was \"dozens.\" The sailors reportedly became ill at sea, two weeks after a port call at [[Danang]], Vietnam. The initial cases were airlifted to a military hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]], where she docked on March 27, 2020, and all 5,000 aboard were ordered to be tested for the virus.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 /><ref name=\"NBC Gains Griffith\">{{cite news |last1=Gains |first1=Mosheh |last2=Griffith |first2=Janelle |title=Coronavirus outbreak diverts Navy aircraft carrier to Guam, all 5,000 aboard to be tested |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-diverts-navy-aircraft-carrier-guam-all-5-000-n1169726 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> About 100 affected sailors were off-loaded, and the rest of the crew remained on board. On March 30, Crozier emailed a four-page internal letter to Naval leaders, pleading to have most of the crew evacuated and quarantined ashore, saying it was impossible to follow social-distancing and quarantine procedures on a crowded ship. On March 31, the letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php|title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias|last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe|date=March 31, 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier evacuated, with a skeleton crew of 400 to remain aboard to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, and the galley.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Crozier was relieved of command by acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]] [[Thomas Modly]]. At the time of his removal, some 114 crew members (of a total complement of about 4,000) had been reported to be positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=April 3, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/politics/uss-roosevelt-commander-relieved/index.html|title=Commander of aircraft carrier hit by coronavirus removed for 'poor judgment' after sounding alarm|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Zachary Cohen |author3=Jamie Crawford|website=CNN|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Borger|first=Julian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/02/us-navy-uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus|title=US navy fires commander who raised alarm about coronavirus on ship|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> As he disembarked, sailors chanted \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\"; a video of the chanting was posted to Twitter and captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=April 3, 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946|first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref> As of April 6, 2020, the ship was docked at Guam, where most of the sailors were being offloaded for quarantine. According to Modly, about 140 sailors have tested positive for COVID-19, of whom 95 are symptomatic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barrett |first1=Claire |title=Theodore Roosevelt captain followed in footsteps of ship\u2019s namesake by writing bombshell letter |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2020/04/04/theodore-roosevelt-captain-followed-in-footsteps-of-ships-namesake-by-writing-bombshell-letter/ |website=navytimes.com |publisher=Sightline Media Group |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Crozier reportedly began showing symptoms of coronavirus before he was removed from ''Theodore Roosevelt'', according to two of his Naval Academy classmates. It was later announced that he has tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ismay|first=John|title=Navy Captain Removed From Carrier Tests Positive for Covid-19|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/magazine/navy-captain-crozier-positive-coronavirus.html|date=April 5, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement to reporters, Modly said \"[Crozier's conduct] raised alarm bells unnecessarily. It undermines our efforts and the chain of command\u2019s efforts to address this problem, and creates a panic and this perception that the Navy\u2019s not on the job, that the government\u2019s not on the job, and it's just not true.\" Modly also criticized Crozier's decision to send the letter over non-secure, unclassified systems. \"He decided to send an email and copy that email to a large list of other people who were not in the chain of command, and sent it up also through the chain of command skipping people in the chain of command,\" Modly said. \"And that, to me, just represented just extremely poor judgment, because once you do that in this digital era, you know that there is no way that you can control where that information's going to go.\" Modly said \"[There are] other ships that are out there in the Pacific that are now perhaps on higher standard of alert because our adversaries in the region think that one of our warships might be crippled, which it's not.\"<ref name=NYPost20200403>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/03/navy-secretary-says-ousted-ship-capt-brett-crozier-put-sailors-at-risk/ |date=2020-04-03 |title=Navy Secretary says ousted ship Capt. Brett Crozier put sailors \u2018at risk\u2019 with coronavirus alarm\" |publisher=[[New York Post]] |last1=Nelson |first1=Steven}}</ref> Modly also pointed out the effect the letter might have on adversaries: \"It raised concerns about the operational security and operational capability of that ship that could have emboldened our adversaries to seek advantage\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aaro |first1=David |title=Acting Navy secretary 'had no discussions' with White House prior to firing Crozier: report |url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/acting-navy-secretary-had-no-discussions-white-house-before-firing |website=Fox News |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone /> On 6 April Modly visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship\u2019s [[public address system]]. In it he excoriated Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as \u2018Stupid\u2019 |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The next day Modly apologized and retracted the comment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing|title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis|last2=Aaro|first2=David|date=April 7, 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Later the same day, Modly resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262|title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\nA joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, Representative [[Adam Smith (politician)|Adam Smith]] (a member of the Democratic party, representing the State of Washington), criticized Crozier's conduct, saying \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately.\" The statement also said \"[R]elieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=NPR}}</ref> President [[Donald Trump]] criticized Crozier's letter on April 4, 2020, saying \"I thought it was terrible, what he did, to write a letter. This isn't a class on literature. This is a captain of a massive ship that's nuclear-powered.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html|title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible'|last=Feuer|first=William|date=2020-04-04|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards, and decorations ==\n{| style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|221px|center]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=award-oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Service Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Battle Effectiveness Award ribbon, 2nd award.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar.svg|width=106}} \n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=United States Navy Rifle Marksmanship Ribbon with expert device.svg|width=106px}} \n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=United States Navy Pistol Marksmanship Ribbon with expert device.svg|width=106px}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Navy_CaS.png|50px]] \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[Naval Aviator Badge]]\n|-\n|[[Legion of Merit]] w/ 1 gold [[service star]]\n|[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ 1 silver [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[Air Medal]]\n|[[Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n|[[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] w/ 2 gold [[service stars]]\n|-\n|[[Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]] w/ 1 gold [[service star]]\n|[[Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n|[[Navy E Ribbon]] w/ 2 [[Battle E]] devices\n|-\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]]\n|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|-\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|[[Navy Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]] w/ 3 [[service stars]]\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Navy & Marine Corps Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|[[NATO Medal]]\n|[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Rifle Marksmanship Medal]] w/ \"E\" device\n|[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Pistol Marksmanship Medal]] w/ \"E\" device\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[Command at Sea insignia]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Round-Robin Letter (Spanish\u2013American War)]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Brett E. Crozier}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20191102225443/https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/pages/commandingofficer.aspx Navy biography]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crozier, Brett}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Rosa, California]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:United States Navy captains]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{redirect|Captain Crozier|the Irish polar explorer|Francis Crozier}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|United States Navy officer}}\n\n{{infobox military person\n|name=Brett E. Crozier\n|image=Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg\n|birth_name=Brett Elliott Crozier<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/102nd-congress/852 |title=PN852 \u2014 Navy |date=March 3, 1992 |website=[[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|02|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], [[California]], U.S.\n|allegiance=[[United States of America]]\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|rank=[[File:US Navy O6 infobox.svg|23px]] [[Captain_(United_States_O-6)#U.S._Navy|Captain]] (U.S. rank O-6)<!---specified O-6 to avoid confusion with the more widely known but much lower O-3 rank in the army that bears the same name, for the understanding of ordinary readers not having specialist knowledge--->\n|serviceyears=1992\u2013present\n|commands=[[VFA-94]]<br/>{{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}<br/>{{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71}}\n|battles=[[Iraq War]]\n|awards=[[File:Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|23px]] [[Legion of Merit]] (2) <small>([[#Honors, awards, and decorations|more]])</small>\n}}\n'''Brett Elliott Crozier''' (born February 24, 1970) is a [[Captain_(United_States_O-6)#U.S._Navy|Captain]] in the [[United States Navy]]. He served as [[commanding officer]] of the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']] until being relieved on April 2, 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Courtney|last=Kube|first2=Mosheh|last2=Gains|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier|work=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCrozier grew up in [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], California, graduating from [[Santa Rosa High School (Santa Rosa, California)|Santa Rosa High School]] in 1988 and then entering the [[U.S. Naval Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10310811-181/chris-smith-santa-rosa-high |archive-url=https://archive.is/uI1PU |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Santa Rosa High grad and \u2018Top Gun\u2019 fan now commands the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt |date=November 14, 2019 |last1=Smith |first1=Chris |publisher=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref> He graduated from the Academy in 1992. He received his Master\u2019s Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies from the [[Naval War College]] in 2007, and completed [[Nuclear Power School]] in 2014.<ref name=\"NavyBio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/Pages/COMMANDINGOFFICER.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/ZJbJV |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Captain Brett E. Crozier |publisher=US Navy}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nCrozier was designated a [[naval aviator]] in 1994, and was assigned as a [[SH-60B Seahawk]] pilot to HSL-37 at Barbers Point, Hawaii. He deployed on board {{USS|Crommelin|FFG-37|6}} and {{USS|Fletcher|DD-992|6}} for operations in the Pacific Ocean and [[Operation Southern Watch]] in the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref name = blueridge>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/lcc19/Pages/Bio1-9June2017-16June2018.aspx|title=Captain Brett E. Crozier|website=www.public.navy.mil|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Crozier served in Navy Personnel Command as an aviation detailer and retention program manager. He then shifted to flying the [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18 Hornet]]. In 2002, he reported to [[VFA-97|Strike Fighter Squadron 97 (VFA-97)]], the \"Warhawks\"; the following year, the squadron deployed with {{USS|Nimitz}} in support of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] (OIF).<ref name = blueridge/>\n\nIn 2004, Crozier reported to [[VFA-94|Strike Fighter Squadron 94 (VFA-94)]], another F/A-18 Hornet unit known as the Mighty Shrikes, as a department head, and was again deployed with ''Nimitz'' in 2005. In 2006, Crozier was assigned to [[VFA-125]], the \"Rough Raiders,\" and served as an instructor and Fleet Replacement Squadron Operations Officer. The following year, he reported in 2007 to the Naval War College, where he earned a Master's Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies. \n\nCrozier later served as the [[executive officer]], then commanding officer of VFA-94, based at Naval Station Lemoore in California. As squadron CO, he made multiple deployments for U.S. [[United States Third Fleet|Third]], [[United States Fifth Fleet|Fifth]], and [[United States Seventh Fleet|Seventh Fleet]] operations, numerous exercises and Operations Southern Watch and OIF.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> He led his squadron on expeditionary deployments with [[Marine Aircraft Group 12]] based out of [[Marine Corps Air Station Iwakuni]], Japan, to support Pacific operations and the [[Global War on Terror]]. His squadron CO tour ended in August 2010. \n\nCrozier then reported to [[Naval Striking and Support Forces NATO]] in [[Naples]], Italy, and served as the lead air planner for Joint Task Force Odyssey Dawn and Combined Joint Task Force Deputy Director of Targeting for NATO's Operation Unified Protector.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> \n\nFrom April 2014 until July 2016, Crozier completed the naval nuclear power training program and served as the executive officer of {{USS|Ronald Reagan}}. During this tour,  ''Reagan'' took part in [[Rim of the Pacific|RIMPAC 2014]], two maintenance availabilities, a forward deployment to [[Yokosuka, Japan]], to relieve {{USS|George Washington|CVN-73|6}} as the U.S. Navy's only forward-deployed aircraft carrier, and several Forward Deployed Naval Force deployments in the [[United States Indo-Pacific Command]] area of responsibility.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> From June 2017 to November 2018, he commanded the amphibious command ship {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19|6}} while the ship completed an extensive dry-dock refit and then returned to operations at sea.<ref name=\"blueridge\" /> He was assigned command of the [[Nuclear propulsion|nuclear]] [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in November 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/us/politics/coronavirus-aircraft-carrier-roosevelt-crozier.html|title=He Led a Top Navy Ship. Now He Sits in Quarantine, Fired and Infected.|last1=Schmitt|first1=Eric|last2=Ismay|first2=John|date=April 5, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 outbreak onboard ''Theodore Roosevelt''===\n[[File:CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg|thumb|right|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019, one month before Crozier took command of the vessel]]\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\nCrozier was captain of ''Theodore Roosevelt'', then deployed in the Pacific, on March 24, 2020 when reports indicated that three members of the crew had tested positive for [[COVID-19]]. The next day the number of affected sailors was increased to eight, and within a few days it was \"dozens.\" The sailors reportedly became ill at sea, two weeks after a port call at [[Danang]], Vietnam. The initial cases were airlifted to a military hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]], where she docked on March 27, 2020, and all 5,000 aboard were ordered to be tested for the virus.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 /><ref name=\"NBC Gains Griffith\">{{cite news |last1=Gains |first1=Mosheh |last2=Griffith |first2=Janelle |title=Coronavirus outbreak diverts Navy aircraft carrier to Guam, all 5,000 aboard to be tested |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-diverts-navy-aircraft-carrier-guam-all-5-000-n1169726 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> About 100 affected sailors were off-loaded, and the rest of the crew remained on board. On March 30, Crozier emailed a four-page internal letter to Naval leaders, pleading to have most of the crew evacuated and quarantined ashore, saying it was impossible to follow social-distancing and quarantine procedures on a crowded ship. On March 31, the letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php|title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias|last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe|date=March 31, 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier evacuated, with a skeleton crew of 400 to remain aboard to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, and the galley.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Crozier was relieved of command by acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]] [[Thomas Modly]]. At the time of his removal, some 114 crew members (of a total complement of about 4,000) had been reported to be positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=April 3, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/politics/uss-roosevelt-commander-relieved/index.html|title=Commander of aircraft carrier hit by coronavirus removed for 'poor judgment' after sounding alarm|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Zachary Cohen |author3=Jamie Crawford|website=CNN|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Borger|first=Julian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/02/us-navy-uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus|title=US navy fires commander who raised alarm about coronavirus on ship|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> As he disembarked, sailors chanted \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\"; a video of the chanting was posted to Twitter and captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=April 3, 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946|first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref> As of April 6, 2020, the ship was docked at Guam, where most of the sailors were being offloaded for quarantine. According to Modly, about 140 sailors have tested positive for COVID-19, of whom 95 are symptomatic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barrett |first1=Claire |title=Theodore Roosevelt captain followed in footsteps of ship\u2019s namesake by writing bombshell letter |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2020/04/04/theodore-roosevelt-captain-followed-in-footsteps-of-ships-namesake-by-writing-bombshell-letter/ |website=navytimes.com |publisher=Sightline Media Group |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Crozier reportedly began showing symptoms of coronavirus before he was removed from ''Theodore Roosevelt'', according to two of his Naval Academy classmates. It was later announced that he has tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ismay|first=John|title=Navy Captain Removed From Carrier Tests Positive for Covid-19|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/magazine/navy-captain-crozier-positive-coronavirus.html|date=April 5, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement to reporters, Modly said \"[Crozier's conduct] raised alarm bells unnecessarily. It undermines our efforts and the chain of command\u2019s efforts to address this problem, and creates a panic and this perception that the Navy\u2019s not on the job, that the government\u2019s not on the job, and it's just not true.\" Modly also criticized Crozier's decision to send the letter over non-secure, unclassified systems. \"He decided to send an email and copy that email to a large list of other people who were not in the chain of command, and sent it up also through the chain of command skipping people in the chain of command,\" Modly said. \"And that, to me, just represented just extremely poor judgment, because once you do that in this digital era, you know that there is no way that you can control where that information's going to go.\" Modly said \"[There are] other ships that are out there in the Pacific that are now perhaps on higher standard of alert because our adversaries in the region think that one of our warships might be crippled, which it's not.\"<ref name=NYPost20200403>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/03/navy-secretary-says-ousted-ship-capt-brett-crozier-put-sailors-at-risk/ |date=2020-04-03 |title=Navy Secretary says ousted ship Capt. Brett Crozier put sailors \u2018at risk\u2019 with coronavirus alarm\" |publisher=[[New York Post]] |last1=Nelson |first1=Steven}}</ref> Modly also pointed out the effect the letter might have on adversaries: \"It raised concerns about the operational security and operational capability of that ship that could have emboldened our adversaries to seek advantage\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aaro |first1=David |title=Acting Navy secretary 'had no discussions' with White House prior to firing Crozier: report |url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/acting-navy-secretary-had-no-discussions-white-house-before-firing |website=Fox News |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, Acting U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone /> On 6 April Modly visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship\u2019s [[public address system]]. In it he excoriated Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as \u2018Stupid\u2019 |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The next day Modly apologized and retracted the comment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing|title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis|last2=Aaro|first2=David|date=April 7, 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Later the same day, Modly resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262|title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\nA joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, Representative [[Adam Smith (politician)|Adam Smith]] (a member of the Democratic party, representing the State of Washington), criticized Crozier's conduct, saying \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately.\" The statement also said \"[R]elieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=NPR}}</ref> President [[Donald Trump]] criticized Crozier's letter on April 4, 2020, saying \"I thought it was terrible, what he did, to write a letter. This isn't a class on literature. This is a captain of a massive ship that's nuclear-powered.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html|title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible'|last=Feuer|first=William|date=2020-04-04|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards, and decorations ==\n{| style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|221px|center]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=award-oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Service Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2